  "prompt": "How many pictures does a 2GB SD card hold?",
  "response": "The number of pictures a 2GB SD card can hold depends entirely on the following factors:\n\n*   **Resolution (Megapixels):** Higher resolution means larger file sizes. A 12MP picture will take up more space than a 6MP picture.\n*   **Image Format:** JPG/JPEG is a compressed format, while RAW is uncompressed (or less compressed) and retains more detail. RAW files are much larger.\n*   **Compression Quality (for JPG):** Lower compression (higher quality) results in larger file sizes.\n*   **Image Content:** Detailed, complex scenes (lots of colors, textures) tend to compress less effectively than simple, uniform scenes, leading to larger file sizes.\n*   **Video Files:** Any video recorded on the card takes up significantly more space than images.\n\n**Estimating Based on Typical Scenarios:**\n\nLet's assume we're talking about **JPG format** pictures.\n\n*   **Low Resolution (e.g., 5MP):** A 5MP JPG might average around 1MB-2MB per picture.  A 2GB card (which has roughly 2000MB of usable space) could hold approximately **1000-2000 pictures.**\n*   **Medium Resolution (e.g., 10MP):** A 10MP JPG might average around 2MB-4MB per picture. A 2GB card could hold approximately **500-1000 pictures.**\n*   **High Resolution (e.g., 20MP or higher):** A 20MP JPG or higher might average around 4MB-8MB+ per picture. A 2GB card could hold approximately **250-500 pictures or fewer.**\n\n**If you're shooting RAW:**\n\n*   RAW files are significantly larger, often 2-5 times the size of a high-quality JPG. You might only get **50-200 RAW images** on a 2GB card, depending on the camera.\n\n**Key Takeaway:**\n\nThere's no single answer. You really need to consider your camera's settings and typical file sizes to get a realistic estimate.\n\n**How to Find Out:**\n\nThe best way to know is to:\n\n1.  **Take a few test shots with your camera using your desired settings (resolution, format, quality).**\n2.  **Transfer those pictures to your computer and check the average file size.**\n3.  **Divide the SD card's capacity (approximately 2000MB for a 2GB card) by the average file size.**\n\nExample:\n\n*   You take 5 test shots at 12MP in JPG format.\n*   You transfer them to your computer and see that the average file size is 3MB.\n*   2000MB / 3MB = Approximately 666 pictures.\n\nTherefore, you can estimate that a 2GB card would hold around 666 pictures with those settings.\n",
